Voting

What is the measure?

The share of voters in Santa Barbara who cast ballots for each party in presidential elections from 2000 to 2020.

Why is it important?

Voting trends by residents of Santa Barbara County reflect shifting political preferences in the region. Similar trends are found in the nation as a whole and may indicate increasing ideological division between parties.

How are we doing?

In 2000, voters in Santa Barbara County voted in near equal percentages for the Democratic and Republican candidates, Al Gore and George W. Bush, at 47.29% and 46.06% respectively. Since then, there has been a steady increase in the share of county residents who have voted for the Democratic presidential candidate. In the most recent presidential election, 64.52% of ballots in the county were cast for Joseph R. Biden and 32.63% were cast for Donald J. Trump.

What are the measures?

The share of the eligible population that was registered to vote in each year and the share of registered voters who voted in past elections in Santa Barbara County.

Why are they important?

Voter registration and turnout measure the most basic forms of civic participation, and are surrogate measures for the level of interest residents have in community affairs. Broad-based citizen involvement not only improves the accountability of government, but also creates a critical fabric of support for all our institutions.

How are we doing?

Both voter registration and voting turnout increased in 2020, with 80.56% of eligible individuals registering to vote and 85.64% of registered voters casting a ballot. This was a record share of registered voters and a near-record share of ballots cast. This was the highest voter turnout percentage in a presidential election since 2004, where voter turnout was 85.80%.
